1
00:00:10,416 --> 00:00:11,541
[MALE SALES CLERK 1A]
Plus wi-fi--

2
00:00:11,625 --> 00:00:12,708
[LISA gasps]

3
00:00:17,250 --> 00:00:19,666
[NINE] Choice one, you can
die where you stand.

4
00:00:19,750 --> 00:00:22,208
Or choice two: you can
become an accomplice.

5
00:00:22,291 --> 00:00:23,750
[LISA gasps]

6
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:28,750
[LISA panting]

7
00:00:31,583 --> 00:00:33,791
Lisa, there's no going back.

8
00:00:33,875 --> 00:00:35,416
[LISA gasps]

9
00:02:33,958 --> 00:02:35,625
[NEWS ANCHOR 2A] We're here
at the scene of the bombing.

10
00:02:35,708 --> 00:02:38,750
The police have concluded
this was not an accident.

11
00:02:38,833 --> 00:02:41,458
What we experienced
was an act of terror.

12
00:02:41,541 --> 00:02:42,833
In their official statement,

13
00:02:42,916 --> 00:02:45,916
the police promised to
take down these terrorists.

14
00:02:53,708 --> 00:02:54,791
[LISA'S MOTHER]
Lisa!

15
00:02:54,875 --> 00:02:57,333
Do you know how many
times I texted you?

16
00:02:57,416 --> 00:03:00,000
Why would you wanna
make me worry like that?

17
00:03:00,083 --> 00:03:01,666
I'm sorry, Mom.

18
00:03:01,750 --> 00:03:02,708
[LISA'S MOTHER]
No, you're not.

19
00:03:02,791 --> 00:03:04,208
This is all a part of your plan!

20
00:03:04,291 --> 00:03:05,708
Wha--?

21
00:03:05,791 --> 00:03:07,333
[LISA'S MOTHER] Don't lie to me!
Please tell me the truth.

22
00:03:07,416 --> 00:03:08,875
What are you trying to do to me?

23
00:03:08,958 --> 00:03:10,250
[LISA]
Please stop.

24
00:03:10,333 --> 00:03:12,208
Are you planning to run away
just like your father?

25
00:03:12,291 --> 00:03:16,041
You're going to leave me, too.
I won't allow it! Lisa! No!

26
00:03:16,125 --> 00:03:17,833
[LISA grunting]

27
00:03:17,916 --> 00:03:21,333
[LISA'S MOTHER]
Come back here! Lisa!

28
00:03:21,416 --> 00:03:28,750
[LISA panting]

29
00:03:28,833 --> 00:03:32,708
[LISA]
In that moment, I was terrified.

30
00:03:35,458 --> 00:03:37,291
[LISA]
It wasn't my mother, though.

31
00:03:37,375 --> 00:03:40,083
I was afraid of something else.

32
00:03:40,166 --> 00:03:43,375
[NINE]
Lisa, there's no going back.

33
00:03:43,458 --> 00:03:45,333
[LISA]
The words he said,

34
00:03:45,416 --> 00:03:47,916
and how cold they made me feel.

35
00:03:56,666 --> 00:03:58,166
[KURAHASHI] Can those in
the back hear all right?

36
00:03:58,250 --> 00:03:59,583
[MALE INVESTIGATOR 2A]
Yes sir, we can hear.

37
00:03:59,666 --> 00:04:00,708
[MALE INVESTIGATOR 2B]
Sounds fine to me.

38
00:04:00,791 --> 00:04:02,500
[KURAHASHI]
Welcome. I'm Kurahashi.

39
00:04:02,583 --> 00:04:05,875
The First Investigation
Division Chief. To start with,

40
00:04:05,958 --> 00:04:08,166
we'll hear updates from
the different departments.

41
00:04:08,250 --> 00:04:11,166
All right. Director Shimada
will share casualties.

42
00:04:11,250 --> 00:04:13,000
[SHIMADA]
Thank you.

43
00:04:13,083 --> 00:04:15,166
Before the Government
Offices collapse,

44
00:04:15,250 --> 00:04:16,916
the building's fire alarm
was triggered

45
00:04:17,000 --> 00:04:18,916
allowing a full evacuation.

46
00:04:19,000 --> 00:04:21,166
As far as we know,
there were no fatalities.

47
00:04:21,250 --> 00:04:23,375
There were 27 injuries reported,

48
00:04:23,458 --> 00:04:25,458
but they were all
relatively minor.

49
00:04:25,541 --> 00:04:27,750
We got lucky on this one, guys.

50
00:04:27,833 --> 00:04:29,708
Considering the scale
of the damage,

51
00:04:29,791 --> 00:04:31,875
these numbers are extremely low.

52
00:04:31,958 --> 00:04:33,083
[KURAHASHI]
Thank you, and now

53
00:04:33,166 --> 00:04:35,375
to Division Chief Kinoshita
from Cybercrime.

54
00:04:35,458 --> 00:04:37,000
[KINOSHITA]
Thanks.

55
00:04:37,083 --> 00:04:39,666
Regarding the video the
alleged suspects uploaded

56
00:04:39,750 --> 00:04:41,583
on the day the
incident occurred,

57
00:04:41,666 --> 00:04:43,458
there's not much to report yet.

58
00:04:43,541 --> 00:04:45,166
We know they used
anonymity software

59
00:04:45,250 --> 00:04:48,000
called Tor when
accessing the Internet.

60
00:04:48,083 --> 00:04:50,916
So, basically, it's impossible
to determine their IP address.

61
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:54,083
[HAMURA] Excuse me!
I'm Hamura from First Division.

62
00:04:54,166 --> 00:04:56,000
From watching the video,
it seems like the suspects

63
00:04:56,083 --> 00:04:57,583
are a couple of kids.

64
00:04:57,666 --> 00:05:00,583
Is there any way to find out if
their threat was the real deal?

65
00:05:00,666 --> 00:05:04,041
It's possible. We are
analyzing the video again.

66
00:05:04,125 --> 00:05:07,708
[KURAHASHI] Next up. Okano,
head of Special Investigations.

67
00:05:07,791 --> 00:05:09,625
He'll be reporting on
the surveillance video

68
00:05:09,708 --> 00:05:10,833
from the crime scene.

69
00:05:10,916 --> 00:05:13,625
[OKANO]
Yes, at this point in time,

70
00:05:13,708 --> 00:05:16,750
we have not found anyone
that looks like the suspects.

71
00:05:16,833 --> 00:05:18,083
Thanks to the
large-scale blackout

72
00:05:18,166 --> 00:05:19,666
right before the incident,

73
00:05:19,750 --> 00:05:21,416
the cameras stopped
for a period of time,

74
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:23,166
and it is believed they
placed the bombs

75
00:05:23,250 --> 00:05:25,541
in the 25 minutes it took
for the backup generators

76
00:05:25,625 --> 00:05:27,458
to kick in.

77
00:05:27,541 --> 00:05:28,916
[HAMURA]
Sorry, but,

78
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:31,166
are we also looking into the
possibility these suspects

79
00:05:31,250 --> 00:05:32,500
might have been
behind the blackout?

80
00:05:32,583 --> 00:05:34,375
[INVESTIGATORS murmur]

81
00:05:34,458 --> 00:05:35,708
[KURAHASHI]
The Special Investigation team

82
00:05:35,791 --> 00:05:37,625
is following up on that, now.

83
00:05:37,708 --> 00:05:39,208
That's correct.
We're in the process

84
00:05:39,291 --> 00:05:40,916
of interviewing the
construction workers

85
00:05:41,000 --> 00:05:44,291
involved with the crane accident
that caused the outage.

86
00:05:44,375 --> 00:05:46,958
[KURAHASHI] Finally, Section
Chief Hamada from Forensics.

87
00:05:47,041 --> 00:05:49,750
Please give us your professional
opinion about the bomb.

88
00:05:49,833 --> 00:05:53,500
Yes, sir. But, before
that, I'd like to talk about

89
00:05:53,583 --> 00:05:55,458
the structure of
the government office.

90
00:05:55,541 --> 00:05:57,500
The pillars that support
the frame of the building are,

91
00:05:57,583 --> 00:05:59,458
in fact, four times
thicker than usual,

92
00:05:59,541 --> 00:06:01,083
and due to that
particular strength,

93
00:06:01,166 --> 00:06:03,416
they are commonly
referred to as "super pillars."

94
00:06:03,500 --> 00:06:05,125
They were created
with attacks in mind,

95
00:06:05,208 --> 00:06:08,541
so they can't be destroyed
by standard bombs.

96
00:06:08,625 --> 00:06:10,041
To be clear.

97
00:06:10,125 --> 00:06:12,958
You're telling us these were
not run-of-the-mill devices?

98
00:06:13,041 --> 00:06:15,125
Thermite reaction
tells you they weren't.

99
00:06:15,208 --> 00:06:17,541
Um, an on-site
investigation detected

100
00:06:17,625 --> 00:06:19,458
the chemical reaction
was present.

101
00:06:19,541 --> 00:06:21,083
A thermite reaction?

102
00:06:21,166 --> 00:06:24,166
Is that unusual in
your experience, Chief?

103
00:06:24,250 --> 00:06:25,625
[HAMADA]
No, on the contrary,

104
00:06:25,708 --> 00:06:28,416
this reaction's extremely
common. As a matter of fact,

105
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:31,083
it's an everyday practice
for welding metal.

106
00:06:31,166 --> 00:06:33,666
To put it very simply,
if a mixture of iron oxide

107
00:06:33,750 --> 00:06:35,416
and aluminum powder is ignited,

108
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:37,250
it produces a large
amount of heat.

109
00:06:37,333 --> 00:06:40,791
[HAMADA]
Up to 3,000 degrees Celsius.

110
00:06:40,875 --> 00:06:42,375
Such a high temperature
is greater than

111
00:06:42,458 --> 00:06:44,708
the melting point of
both iron and concrete,

112
00:06:44,791 --> 00:06:48,500
which means the reaction has
the ability to melt either one.

113
00:06:48,583 --> 00:06:50,791
The ingredients required
to create such a reaction

114
00:06:50,875 --> 00:06:54,041
are also quite a bit easier
to obtain than gunpowder.

115
00:06:54,125 --> 00:06:55,750
Are you're saying
this is what was used

116
00:06:55,833 --> 00:06:57,041
to melt the pillars?

117
00:06:57,125 --> 00:06:58,916
[HAMADA]
It more than likely was, yes.

118
00:06:59,000 --> 00:07:02,000
The purpose of the mixture
was to set off the fire alarms.

119
00:07:02,083 --> 00:07:04,458
Then, once the water from the
sprinklers combined with it,

120
00:07:04,541 --> 00:07:07,125
a phreatic explosion
was created.

121
00:07:07,208 --> 00:07:09,375
At that point, the pillars,
unable to withstand

122
00:07:09,458 --> 00:07:11,000
the weight of the
building, collapsed

123
00:07:11,083 --> 00:07:12,833
along with the structure.

124
00:07:12,916 --> 00:07:14,500
There have not been
many terrorist attacks

125
00:07:14,583 --> 00:07:16,541
that have used this
method in the past.

126
00:07:16,625 --> 00:07:19,083
However, these bombers
didn't just use the reaction,

127
00:07:19,166 --> 00:07:21,541
they planned for the
phreatic explosion as well.

128
00:07:21,625 --> 00:07:23,041
Whoever is behind this assault

129
00:07:23,125 --> 00:07:25,916
is without a doubt
extremely intelligent.

130
00:07:27,375 --> 00:07:28,916
[HAMADA]
That being said,

131
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:31,833
there's still one thing
I can't figure out.

132
00:07:31,916 --> 00:07:33,208
[SHIMADA]
And that would be?

133
00:07:33,291 --> 00:07:34,958
[HAMADA] Strangely enough,
there was a single

134
00:07:35,041 --> 00:07:37,250
TNT bomb used in the attack.

135
00:07:37,333 --> 00:07:39,208
In no way could that have
been necessary to cause

136
00:07:39,291 --> 00:07:42,333
the collapse of the building,
so I decided to reconstruct

137
00:07:42,416 --> 00:07:44,625
the TNT bomb myself
to see if I could find out

138
00:07:44,708 --> 00:07:45,833
why it was there.

139
00:07:45,916 --> 00:07:47,041
What?

140
00:07:47,125 --> 00:07:48,708
I didn't know you could
reconstruct a bomb.

141
00:07:48,791 --> 00:07:51,958
Oh, it's not all that difficult
when TNT is being used.

142
00:07:52,041 --> 00:07:55,166
Anyway, on the TNT, I found
letters that looked like

143
00:07:55,250 --> 00:07:57,083
they had been written
by the bombers.

144
00:07:57,166 --> 00:07:58,333
And?

145
00:07:58,416 --> 00:08:00,458
[HAMADA]
This is what I discovered.

146
00:08:01,875 --> 00:08:03,583
[HAMADA]
You can see them very clearly.

147
00:08:03,666 --> 00:08:07,458
Three letters. V-O-N.

148
00:08:24,416 --> 00:08:26,375
[KURAHASHI] Can you believe
Public Safety is letting

149
00:08:26,458 --> 00:08:28,666
First Division lead a
terrorist investigation?

150
00:08:28,750 --> 00:08:29,916
[SHIMADA]
Of course.

151
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,958
If this thing turns into
a worst-case scenario,

152
00:08:33,041 --> 00:08:35,041
both the media and
the police department

153
00:08:35,125 --> 00:08:37,750
want to be certain they
can still cover it up.

154
00:08:37,833 --> 00:08:39,833
V-O-N.

155
00:08:39,916 --> 00:08:41,208
[SHIMADA]
Yeah.

156
00:08:41,291 --> 00:08:44,416
Guess we know it's connected
to that recent theft.

157
00:08:47,041 --> 00:08:50,333
[SHIMADA] If the public
finds out, they'll panic.

158
00:08:50,416 --> 00:08:51,750
[KURAHASHI]
Indeed, they will.

159
00:08:51,833 --> 00:08:54,125
We need to consider the
likelihood that these attackers

160
00:08:54,208 --> 00:08:56,208
are not with an
existing terrorist cell.

161
00:08:56,291 --> 00:08:57,500
[SHIMADA]
I agree.

162
00:08:57,583 --> 00:08:59,458
But the Public
Safety Bureau does not,

163
00:08:59,541 --> 00:09:01,583
and we're supposed to be
cooperating with them--

164
00:09:01,666 --> 00:09:02,958
indirectly, of course.

165
00:09:03,041 --> 00:09:04,541
No surprise there.

166
00:09:04,625 --> 00:09:08,083
If things don't go well, they
want the freedom to blame us.

167
00:09:21,250 --> 00:09:22,625
Huh?

168
00:09:28,791 --> 00:09:32,958
[TWELVE] Hey Nine, did you
catch that news report?

169
00:09:33,041 --> 00:09:34,708
[NINE] Assume you mean
the one comparing us

170
00:09:34,791 --> 00:09:36,166
to the Unabomber.

171
00:09:36,250 --> 00:09:37,541
[TWELVE]
That's the one!

172
00:09:37,625 --> 00:09:40,750
I was hoping to remind them
of Kenji Sawada, though.

173
00:09:42,708 --> 00:09:44,041
[NINE]
Hear from that girl?

174
00:09:44,125 --> 00:09:45,541
[TWELVE]
Lisa Mishima?

175
00:09:45,625 --> 00:09:46,666
[NINE]
Yeah.

176
00:09:46,750 --> 00:09:48,000
[TWELVE]
You worried?

177
00:09:48,083 --> 00:09:51,541
Nah. I can't imagine she
has the guts to report us.

178
00:09:51,625 --> 00:09:54,916
[TWELVE] Let me ask you
something. Why "accomplice"?

179
00:09:55,000 --> 00:09:58,416
Why use that word when you
were talking to her?

180
00:09:58,500 --> 00:10:00,791
Just trying to scare her.

181
00:10:00,875 --> 00:10:02,583
That's all, huh?

182
00:10:06,375 --> 00:10:08,041
[NINE]
Whose turn?

183
00:10:08,125 --> 00:10:11,625
[TWELVE]
Hmm. One, two,

184
00:10:11,708 --> 00:10:12,708
[NINE, TWELVE]
Three!

185
00:10:23,125 --> 00:10:25,958
[NINE] Hello. Delivery
from Choujyuan Noodles.

186
00:10:26,041 --> 00:10:28,083
Oh. Yeah, just bring it on in.

187
00:10:28,166 --> 00:10:29,625
[NINE]
Cool. Thank you.

188
00:10:45,875 --> 00:10:47,958
Yeah, tried that new
ramen place last night.

189
00:10:48,041 --> 00:10:49,375
You gotta go.

190
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:21,625
[MUKASA]
I don't get you, man.

191
00:11:21,708 --> 00:11:24,750
How can you work
on a crossword puzzle?

192
00:11:24,833 --> 00:11:25,875
First Division looks like

193
00:11:25,958 --> 00:11:27,833
they're in serious
trouble, you know.

194
00:11:27,916 --> 00:11:31,041
But I guess that doesn't affect
us down here in archives.

195
00:11:31,125 --> 00:11:34,291
[SHIBAZAKI] Which is why you're
just screwing around online.

196
00:11:34,375 --> 00:11:35,708
Hey, help me out.

197
00:11:35,791 --> 00:11:38,125
Do you know what the
"instant pork ramen from 1987

198
00:11:38,208 --> 00:11:39,750
that was recently reissued" is?

199
00:11:39,833 --> 00:11:41,041
Oh, come on!

200
00:11:41,125 --> 00:11:42,833
Maybe you could help
me out and not assume

201
00:11:42,916 --> 00:11:45,541
all fat people are
experts on carbs, yeah?

202
00:11:45,625 --> 00:11:47,875
Oh. Try Toppa Chikara
Kusa Yantsuki.

203
00:11:47,958 --> 00:11:51,291
Ah. T.O.P.

204
00:11:51,375 --> 00:11:53,583
[MUKASA] And I'm not screwing
around, by the way.

205
00:11:53,666 --> 00:11:55,875
I'm secretly and covertly
trying to figure out

206
00:11:55,958 --> 00:11:58,875
what Sphinx's next
move could be.

207
00:11:58,958 --> 00:12:02,541
[MUKASA gasps] Too late!
They released a new video!

208
00:12:04,750 --> 00:12:06,958
[NINE]
I'm Sphinx Number One.

209
00:12:07,041 --> 00:12:10,083
[TWELVE] I'm Sphinx Two,
and I heart explosions!

210
00:12:10,166 --> 00:12:13,125
Did you enjoy the fireworks at
the Tokyo Government Office?

211
00:12:13,208 --> 00:12:17,166
All that excitement came from
our very own handmade bombs.

212
00:12:17,250 --> 00:12:18,916
He worked pretty
hard on it, too!

213
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,375
[NINE] This is only the
beginning of the party, though!

214
00:12:21,458 --> 00:12:25,583
In the very near future, we'll
be setting off a second bomb!

215
00:12:25,666 --> 00:12:27,333
[NINE]
We have a riddle for everyone.

216
00:12:27,416 --> 00:12:29,083
Specifically those of you
from law enforcement.

217
00:12:29,166 --> 00:12:30,125
What?

218
00:12:30,208 --> 00:12:31,583
[TWELVE hums]

219
00:12:31,666 --> 00:12:35,333
[NINE] What first walks on
two legs, then on four legs,

220
00:12:35,416 --> 00:12:38,500
and finally on three legs?

221
00:12:38,583 --> 00:12:39,791
[TWELVE]
If you solve the riddle,

222
00:12:39,875 --> 00:12:41,875
then the next bomb
can be yours!

223
00:12:41,958 --> 00:12:42,958
[NINE, TWELVE]
Good luck!

224
00:12:43,041 --> 00:12:45,208
Aw, poor First Division.

225
00:12:45,291 --> 00:12:48,958
Those guys sure as hell won't
be goin' home for a while.

226
00:13:22,541 --> 00:13:25,416
[HAMURA] The hell's
the point of a riddle?

227
00:13:25,500 --> 00:13:28,000
Damn snots need
to learn some respect!

228
00:13:28,083 --> 00:13:29,333
How dare they?

229
00:13:29,416 --> 00:13:32,250
They could just be mouthpieces
for the real guys.

230
00:13:32,333 --> 00:13:35,375
In the long run though,
I guess it doesn't matter.

231
00:13:35,458 --> 00:13:36,916
[door opens]

232
00:13:37,000 --> 00:13:38,333
The last thing
we need right now

233
00:13:38,416 --> 00:13:40,375
is children using bombs as toys.

234
00:13:40,458 --> 00:13:41,583
[HAMURA]
Director Kurahashi.

235
00:13:41,666 --> 00:13:43,166
[KURAHASHI]
The suspects refer to themselves

236
00:13:43,250 --> 00:13:46,791
as "Sphinx," pronouncing it with
a "P" instead of the usual "F".

237
00:13:46,875 --> 00:13:48,375
This isn't from the Egyptian.

238
00:13:48,458 --> 00:13:50,750
It's actually a
Greek pronunciation.

239
00:13:51,958 --> 00:13:53,125
[KURAHASHI]
Sphinx.

240
00:13:53,208 --> 00:13:55,083
Commonly known as one
of the many creatures

241
00:13:55,166 --> 00:13:59,458
from Greek mythology.
It appears in Oedipus Rex.

242
00:13:59,541 --> 00:14:01,500
Laius, Oedipus's father,

243
00:14:01,583 --> 00:14:03,000
