276
00:15:52,125 --> 00:15:55,500
If they didn't give the correct
answer, they would be devoured.

277
00:15:55,583 --> 00:15:59,250
Sounds fun. What kind of
riddles are we talkin'?

278
00:15:59,333 --> 00:16:01,375
"What walks on four
legs in the morning,

279
00:16:01,458 --> 00:16:03,291
on two legs in the afternoon,

280
00:16:03,375 --> 00:16:05,791
and on three legs
in the evening?"

281
00:16:05,875 --> 00:16:08,166
[OKANO, KINOSHITA gasp]
[KURAHASHI] That's right.

282
00:16:08,250 --> 00:16:10,291
[KURAHASHI] It's very similar
to the riddle in the video.

283
00:16:10,375 --> 00:16:12,500
We need to take
these guys seriously.

284
00:16:12,583 --> 00:16:15,750
Okay, if that's the question,
what's the answer?

285
00:16:15,833 --> 00:16:17,250
[KURAHASHI]
The answer is "man."

286
00:16:17,333 --> 00:16:18,250
How come?

287
00:16:18,333 --> 00:16:19,625
I get it.

288
00:16:19,708 --> 00:16:22,375
As an infant, man is forced
to crawl on four legs.

289
00:16:22,458 --> 00:16:24,833
Then as adults, we walk on two.

290
00:16:24,916 --> 00:16:27,166
Elderly people use canes,
which makes three.

291
00:16:27,250 --> 00:16:30,000
Correct. And the times of day?

292
00:16:30,083 --> 00:16:31,708
[KURAHASHI] They represent
the different stages

293
00:16:31,791 --> 00:16:32,875
in a man's life.

294
00:16:32,958 --> 00:16:34,125
[HAMURA]
So how does that relate

295
00:16:34,208 --> 00:16:37,750
to the next bomb
they've set "Man?"

296
00:16:37,833 --> 00:16:39,791
Yeah, or people?

297
00:16:39,875 --> 00:16:43,041
[OKANO] So, a busy shopping area
with a lot of foot traffic?

298
00:16:43,125 --> 00:16:45,250
What if those numbers
match up to an address?

299
00:16:45,333 --> 00:16:48,125
Like Fourth Street, Building
Two-Three or something?

300
00:16:48,208 --> 00:16:52,083
Checking on corresponding
addresses, now.

301
00:16:52,166 --> 00:16:55,791
[KINOSHITA gasps] There's a DNA
research facility in Minato!

302
00:16:55,875 --> 00:16:58,791
[HAMURA] DNA, riddle of man.
That has to be it!

303
00:16:58,875 --> 00:17:00,833
Good enough for me,
let's get a search warrant.

304
00:17:00,916 --> 00:17:02,416
I'm coming, too.

305
00:17:04,041 --> 00:17:09,333
[police sirens blaring]

306
00:17:09,416 --> 00:17:11,833
[OFFICERS] --Come on!
--Let's go!

307
00:17:11,916 --> 00:17:13,583
[CAPTAIN 2A] Move now, people!
[OFFICERS] Yes, sir!

308
00:17:13,666 --> 00:17:14,708
[NEWS ANCHOR 2B]
As of right now.

309
00:17:14,791 --> 00:17:16,083
Police on the scene,
are not giving us

310
00:17:16,166 --> 00:17:17,625
an awful lot of information.

311
00:17:17,708 --> 00:17:19,875
So, we're left to wonder
if the next bomb

312
00:17:19,958 --> 00:17:22,041
is at this DNA
research facility.

313
00:17:22,125 --> 00:17:25,333
It doesn't seem they're any
closer in finding out who--

314
00:17:30,250 --> 00:17:33,208
[phone rings]

315
00:17:33,291 --> 00:17:34,916
Ah, Shibazaki.

316
00:17:35,000 --> 00:17:36,125
[SHIBAZAKI]
Oh good.

317
00:17:36,208 --> 00:17:38,250
You haven't changed
your number on me, yet.

318
00:17:38,333 --> 00:17:39,541
[KURAHASHI]
Not yet.

319
00:17:39,625 --> 00:17:40,791
I've been thinkin'
about that riddle

320
00:17:40,875 --> 00:17:43,083
