bombers left you.

321
00:17:43,166 --> 00:17:44,583
[SHIBAZAKI]
Care to hear my thoughts?

322
00:17:44,666 --> 00:17:49,250
Of course I do. N'you haven't
changed a bit, my friend.

323
00:17:49,333 --> 00:17:53,791
Nope. They're referring to
the mythology of Oedipus.

324
00:17:53,875 --> 00:17:56,083
[KURAHASHI]
Yeah. The answer is "man".

325
00:17:56,166 --> 00:17:57,333
Wrong.

326
00:17:57,416 --> 00:17:59,166
Although "Man" was the
answer to other riddle

327
00:17:59,250 --> 00:18:00,833
the Sphinx was known to ask.

328
00:18:00,916 --> 00:18:03,083
You mean it asked
more than one?

329
00:18:03,166 --> 00:18:04,875
[SHIBAZAKI] Yeah, there's
another lesser-known version

330
00:18:04,958 --> 00:18:08,666
of the story. Two legs in the
morning, four in the afternoon,

331
00:18:08,750 --> 00:18:10,166
and three legs in the evening.

332
00:18:10,250 --> 00:18:12,708
In other words, a
two-four-three progression.

333
00:18:12,791 --> 00:18:13,875
Two-four...?

334
00:18:13,958 --> 00:18:16,833
Meaning the answer
can't be "man" anymore.

335
00:18:16,916 --> 00:18:18,708
[KURAHASHI] So do you
know what the answer is?

336
00:18:18,791 --> 00:18:20,958
[SHIBAZAKI]
Yes, it's Oedipus himself.

337
00:18:21,041 --> 00:18:23,375
Gonna have to
explain that one.

338
00:18:23,458 --> 00:18:25,875
[SHIBAZAKI] He started off
as a man with two legs,

339
